license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Especially recommendable when additonal fans are installed or a fan mod was made.

Hi folks!

Another upgrade item for your Replicator-like 3D printer. These are high feets for the lower corners of your 3d printer.
It is a remix of the basic version.

... better printable threads with less overhang.
... thicker walls, so they make a tight fit without breaking while installing.
... higher than the original for (silent) fan upgrade (which need a higher printer in general). See the picture above looking underneath the printer. The 4 additional fans need space to breath. The feets raise your printer by 20mm, for fan mods with fans up to 25mm (1 inch) thick.
... optional printable bumper for the screw (flexible filament needed, f.e. TPU). I think about to make another bumper for the high feets. Let me know if you need some!
... I recommend to install some soft bumpers (like fabric) on the bottom of the high feets and on the screw (if you have no flexible filaments), to reduce the translation of shaking to the table/cupboard.

I strongly recommend to print just one of these screwable feets and make the other 3 feets static, like in the "feet_set_recommended.stl" file. Because of simple math, 3 feets define a plane, the 4th feet is the "bad one" which is causing the wobbling/tilt of the whole printer. So only one need to be adjustable. I recommend to install the screwable feet at the front, not like me on the back, because most of the weight is on the back, so adjustments are easier when installed on the front.
But it's up to you, if you want to print 4 screwable feets then "just do it". ;)

Have fun.

NOTE
If your screwable feet is much to tight add some PTFE/Teflon lubrication OR resize the x- and y-axis of the screwable feet in your Slicer Software. Try something like 99% or 98%. Do not rescale the z-axis (height)!
The screwable feet is a tight fit with ~0.3mm space between outer and inner thread.

comments.text: If all my steppers on my CTC just stop during a print could it be from bad cooling of stepper drivers.. thanks
comments.author: texday

comments.text:
I think it would be very unlikely if all stop at the same time. Then it would be an electronics problem (maybe broken cable or so).
But if one axis is missing steps, then an overheated stepper driver could be the reason. When stepper drivers like the a4988 or the drv8825 are overheated they stop operation for round about 1 second. For the health of your 3d printer's electronics you should think about active cooling those drivers. I installed two 60mm silent fans on the wooden cover on the bottom blowing on top of the drivers and their heatsinks. Works great for me. ;)

This is a case for the new keyboard-less kindle. It uses the plywood hinge technique, found here on thingiverse. This design was laser cut. A design was etched onto the front of the case, also using the laser cutter.

This design is based upon an original design by Martin Raynesford - please see msraynsford.blogspot.com/2011/11/kindle-case.html.
Basically use the .dxf and open it with the software for your laser cutter. This design is for 3mm plywood. Ensure the power and speed settings are correct (anyone at Nottingham Hackspace, use 320 power and 7 as the speed - everyone else, please ignore that). Then set the machine going.
Give it a good sand. Apply bees wax. Remove excess bees wax and buff to a polish (cheers, Dominic).
Etch any design onto the front.
Drill two holes for a piece of elastic. Thread elastic through the holes and sew together.
You could also use magnets to keep it closed.
Problems are that nothing holds the kindle in the case - maybe use small sticky pads?

description.text:
I wanted a charger cable holder for my nightstand and other places. While it's true there are several to choose from on here, as per Thingiverse tradition, none of them were quite perfectly right for me, but they were still an inspiration:

  • St0nkingByte's 12-slot holder lacked the customizability I needed
  • ryanidt's single holder takes up space on the table surface, which is scarce
  • Amirsf's holder is designed for a horizontal beam, which I don't have
  • xifle's holder needs to be pressed flush against a wall to hold the cable in, which mine isn't
  • bitswype's holder is clever, but requires fairly precise printing to actuate properly, and I didn't want to fight it on my printer.

After looking at the above, I produced this design. It's customizable, mounts flush with #4 wood screws (or other screws if you customize differently), can hold an arbitrary number of cables, and avoids slip-out by locking cables in with a horizontal zip tie or screw+nut. That met all my needs, and maybe it meets yours too?

I like to hunt. I also like to have a few extra shells on the straps of my suspension harness. After not finding a shell holder that would fit my OPW suspension to my satisfaction, I decided to make it on TinkerCAD. This is a clipped, double shell hold that is designed to snuggly fit standard 25mm or 1" strapping found on may suspension and pack systems. If your pack uses 20mm (3/4"), modify the clip-base. https://tinkercad.com/things/e1uKCSv9Ohi-clipped-double-shotgun-shell-holder#

UPDATE: I added a split-clip version after a buddy saw my original. He wanted to be able to clip across the webbing sew-downs, so I split the clip, then had to thicken to prevent easy breakage. Seems to work. You can find it publicly on my Tinkercad page - tjstroker  
I print on a Makerbot Replicator 2. with STANDARD settings. Also found the FAST mode works fine as well. I tapered the clip edges to make it easier to slide in and our of sewn straps, but it still fits snug. If you wish to use with packs/harnesses with smaller strapping, like my Gregory 55L pack (3/4" straps) just go to Tinkerbot and raise the clip-base height a few clicks. I wanted it to fit precise to minimize tilting on the suspension.

description.text:
Regular hex keys are annoying because they are easy to lose and if you have a large number of fasteners to insert or remove, your hands can quickly become sore. The Wiha hex drivers are a great alternative to hex keys that are worth the money if you are constantly working with socket head screws. This tool holder fits both metric and imperial Wiha series 263 hex drivers.
Metric Set Part # Size 26307 0.71mm 26309 0.89mm 26313 1.27mm 26315 1.5mm 26320 2.0mm 26325 2.5mm 26330 3.0mm 26340 4.0mm
Imperial Set Part # Size 26307 0.028" 26309 0.035" 26313 0.050" 26316 1/16" 26320 5/64" 26323 3/32" 26327 7/64" 26331 1/8"
Requires four (2 packages) 3/16" rare earth magnets, RadioShack part #64-1895.

1) Print the holder
2) Drill four small holes on the back for the magnets
3) Attach magnets with CA glue. User kicker if needed.
4) If the holder slides around sanding the back a little or adding a thin coat of rubber cement to the back should solver the problem.

description.text:
I wanted to print this nice model, but it was way to big for my uDelta printer.
I had to reduce the size to 40% of the original. I did this withing Repetier Host itself.
As an result of this, some of the support (at first I used the file including the support) was not sliced, making some of the supportstructures floating in mid-air.

After this I tried the file without the support and add supportstructures with Repetier, but this covered most of the model in supportstructure making this a no-go.
So I decided to import this into Meshmixer. I reduced the size to 40% and then added Meshmixer's support. Saved to .stl and slided it with Repetier.

The endresult is very nice and came out fine. With some different (speed)-settings it would have printed nicer, but after a little paint the print should look perfect.

The .stl file with Meshmixer supports was over 300MB, making me unable to upload it to thingivers. So I slightly reduced the level of details (not even noticeable) to reduce the filesize to just over 100MB.

Changes over the original model:
Modelsize reduced to 40%
Added Meshmixer supportstructures
Reduced Triangles to 82%

Ps. Sorry for choice of colour. I ran out of black filament just before this one.

This is a replacement box for the game Hive ( http://www.gen42.com/hive ). I like the game, but I don't like the zippered carrying pouch that they include in the box. So here's my alternative. The box is large enough to hold all the pieces from the base game.

Print the pieces, keeping an eye on the clearance on your build platform.  It's pretty tight on the ABP, you might need to turn off outline to make it fit.  That's what I did.  Just extrude a bit before you start printing and it will come out fine.
The top fits snugly into the box.  I chose not to treat the surface, so the lid locks in really nicely.  This means that I can turn the box upside down, and the lid will hold the weight of the pieces securely.  This does make it a little difficult to take the lid off, though.
When you process the files in SF, it might start talking about "holes in the triangular mesh" or somesuch.  I don't know what this means, but the box prints really nicely anyhow.  If anyone knows how to avoid this issue, let me know in the comments.

title: Printrbot Plus, V2, CNC Router, 1/16in endmill

description.text: Printrbot Plus V2 dxf with dogbones for CNC routing with 1/16in endmill.

Since Printrbot has stopped selling kits for there bigger printers I needed to produce the parts myself. Using the Printrbot Source files from their website I exported all of the Inventor files to a DXF and added the required dog bones to allow it to be cut with a 1/16in end mill. Successfully built and tested. Make sure you measure your router bit exactly and get the right thickness wood, or it will not work. From there I assembled the printer from the instructions on the Printrbot website. I ordered as much as I could from printrbot.com to give them some money for the great design. The things I couldn't get from them I was able to from amazon and boltdepot.
